1
00:00:00,760 --> 00:00:04,840
Hi, and welcome to a bonus content from Designing Open Democracy.

2
00:00:04,840 --> 00:00:18,320
We previously held a recording on the 11th of March 2020 for a warm up with Ben Ballingall on the talk about his party and how it implements Issues Based Direct Democracy system.

3
00:00:18,320 --> 00:00:21,860
Being that this is a warm up, it is a bit more free-flowing.

4
00:00:21,860 --> 00:00:37,940
However, it explores a bit more into how Flux Party itself works, so you may be finding this to be quite an interesting talk that goes into more details in some aspects of Flux Party that the original talk did not go into.

5
00:00:37,940 --> 00:00:40,800
Hi, and welcome to Designing Open Democracy.

6
00:00:40,820 --> 00:00:45,300
And who we have here is Ben Ballingall from Flux Party.

7
00:00:45,300 --> 00:00:45,820
Hey, Brian.

8
00:00:45,820 --> 00:00:47,820
Thanks for letting me on.

9
00:00:47,820 --> 00:00:49,100
Yes.

10
00:00:49,100 --> 00:00:53,460
So tell me a bit more about Flux Party and what is it?

11
00:00:53,460 --> 00:00:54,300
Ah, cool.

12
00:00:54,300 --> 00:00:56,540
So yeah, I'm with the Flux Party.

13
00:00:56,800 --> 00:01:03,920
We're a political party registered in Australia and also throughout various states throughout Australia.

14
00:01:03,920 --> 00:01:10,240
We're a political party that believes in or proposes issue based direct democracy.

15
00:01:10,240 --> 00:01:22,680
So that's a way for all the citizens or all the citizenry to vote on the issues that come up in parliament and have those results aggregated and shown to a representative.

16
00:01:23,080 --> 00:01:28,220
And our representatives will do what their community votes in parliament.

17
00:01:28,220 --> 00:01:38,100
So if I understand correctly, what you're saying is that it's going to be a system where people will get to do a bit more direct democracy in their government.

18
00:01:38,100 --> 00:01:39,260
Is that correct?

19
00:01:39,260 --> 00:01:40,060
Yeah, truly.

20
00:01:40,980 --> 00:01:45,720
It's a very straight up and down democracy, the people voting on every single issue.

21
00:01:45,720 --> 00:01:46,620
I see.

22
00:01:46,620 --> 00:01:49,060
So tell me a bit more about the history of Flux.

23
00:01:49,260 --> 00:01:54,380
Like you mentioned, Max Kane was a big part of Flux.

24
00:01:54,380 --> 00:01:54,760
Yeah.

25
00:01:54,760 --> 00:01:57,200
So, was it 2000?

26
00:01:57,200 --> 00:02:00,420
Middle of 2015, I believe it was.

27
00:02:00,420 --> 00:02:16,280
Max Kane and Nathan Spataro, who are the co-founders, came together because they had both an idea for this new form of democracy, but most importantly, or perhaps secondly, most importantly, they had the ability and the code behind being able to develop the app.

28
00:02:16,760 --> 00:02:28,120
So, they developed a prototype of the app and then used, I guess, that to generate enough buzz to get the party registered before the 2016 federal election.

29
00:02:28,120 --> 00:02:33,780
So, yeah, late 2015 would have been the true start of vote Flux for just the two of them.

30
00:02:33,780 --> 00:02:34,960
Late 2016?

31
00:02:34,960 --> 00:02:35,660
Yep.

32
00:02:36,100 --> 00:02:36,920
Okay.

33
00:02:36,920 --> 00:02:47,440
Why did we choose to start with, say, electronic voting, rather than, say, like, um, what can I say?

34
00:02:47,440 --> 00:02:50,180
Why is there a need to switch?

35
00:02:50,180 --> 00:02:53,320
Um, I think, well, we've...

36
00:02:53,320 --> 00:03:22,720
Depends on your views of representative government, is one way I'll start that, but for at least a lot of us in Flux, yeah, we see the flaws in representative democracy and the governmental systems we have right now, and that, frankly, a lot of the flaws that we face politically, as, you know, the people, if we can call that, come from a lack of representation, a lack of transparency, and a lack of accountability of our representatives.

37
00:03:22,720 --> 00:03:28,140
So, you know, generating some sort of system, especially one that's democratic and gives...

38
00:03:28,140 --> 00:03:30,920
empowers everybody, you know, it's, it's, I...

39
00:03:30,920 --> 00:03:34,860
personally, I think it's something people have been doing for the entirety of history.

40
00:03:34,900 --> 00:03:39,460
Ours just happens to be based on blockchain tech and the internet.

41
00:03:39,460 --> 00:03:44,440
But, you know, technological innovation has sort of always progressed some sort of political change.

42
00:03:44,440 --> 00:03:44,880
Yeah, I see.

43
00:03:44,880 --> 00:03:46,940
It's just something that everybody sort of felt.

44
00:03:46,940 --> 00:03:49,420
And this is how it manifested more than anything.

45
00:03:49,920 --> 00:03:59,660
I guess it can come out where we're designing open democracy, or at least what I understand of what you're doing, because I'm not fully across designing open democracy.

46
00:03:59,660 --> 00:04:01,580
But it's certainly like, yeah, for sure.

47
00:04:01,580 --> 00:04:12,860
So I see this as like, Flux is one element, if I can, of designing an open democracy, in that Flux posits a true democratic form.

48
00:04:12,860 --> 00:04:15,040
It allows everybody to vote on issues.

49
00:04:15,040 --> 00:04:20,620
Right now, it's contingent on parliament, what is put up in parliament primarily.

50
00:04:20,620 --> 00:04:23,240
So like three-year electoral cycle.

51
00:04:23,240 --> 00:04:23,680
Exactly.

52
00:04:23,680 --> 00:04:28,240
Three-year electoral cycle, we need to get this person in to do this thing.

53
00:04:28,240 --> 00:04:37,000
But what it doesn't sort of, or what will grow, hopefully, symbiotically is how are people going to be informed about these decisions they're going to make?

54
00:04:37,920 --> 00:04:51,820
You know, how do we decide once we've released all these old political parties of leading us, how do we decide what facets of their ideology were good and what were bad?

55
00:04:52,040 --> 00:04:53,960
And how do we actually have these discussions?

56
00:04:56,060 --> 00:04:57,600
That's something that needs to grow.

57
00:04:57,600 --> 00:05:05,900
That's a societal, the people need to develop this thing in tandem with the ability to vote on issues and control their MP.

58
00:05:06,420 --> 00:05:11,680
So, what you're saying is that is Flux only one component of what is needed in the society?

59
00:05:11,680 --> 00:05:13,680
There's a cultural element, is that correct?

60
00:05:13,680 --> 00:05:13,920
Yeah.

61
00:05:13,920 --> 00:05:25,200
because like I think maybe what some people might have a concern is that you could try to fix the way people vote, but is that going to really fundamentally change this conflict we have?

62
00:05:25,200 --> 00:05:31,940
because there's also issue of like say media representation or cultural representation and et cetera.

63
00:05:31,940 --> 00:05:37,460
I think that's the million, billion, trillion dollar question.

64
00:05:38,680 --> 00:05:39,960
And you know, we don't know.

65
00:05:39,960 --> 00:05:46,240
Like when we think of voting, especially nowadays, we think of this voting for a team, voting for a team that has...

66
00:05:46,240 --> 00:05:46,860
Tribalism.

67
00:05:46,860 --> 00:05:51,320
Yeah, this tribal team that's always been this way.

68
00:05:51,320 --> 00:05:55,500
They've always held this ideology that comes with these 50 points.

69
00:05:56,240 --> 00:06:07,260
So, really changing how culture and society looks at politics, looks at it via every issue and how those issues actually relate individually.

70
00:06:07,260 --> 00:06:09,660
Yeah, you know, that's a huge cultural change.

71
00:06:09,660 --> 00:06:12,800
So, it's a huge cultural shift and mentality.

72
00:06:13,220 --> 00:06:21,900
For sure, yeah, the actual mentality, you know, it's totally acceptable to only like one initiative that the Greens put forward.

73
00:06:21,900 --> 00:06:29,200
And then the next week to like a One Nation initiative, people could not even comprehend how that could ever work.

74
00:06:29,200 --> 00:06:34,420
But when you look at individual issues, you know, that Greens issue could be a great environmental issue.

75
00:06:34,420 --> 00:06:39,180
And the One Nation issue is something to do with rural infrastructure.

76
00:06:39,180 --> 00:06:40,940
Like, they can both be right.

77
00:06:41,400 --> 00:06:46,240
And in today's politics, you can't, that's completely, you know, absurd.

78
00:06:46,660 --> 00:06:52,200
So that's a huge change that isn't solved by people being able to vote.

79
00:06:52,200 --> 00:06:53,540
That's not what will come.

80
00:06:53,540 --> 00:07:04,640
So I have this device that you're talking about, like how would the ordinary voter and the Australian public participate in your system?

81
00:07:04,640 --> 00:07:05,280
Yeah, for sure.

82
00:07:05,820 --> 00:07:07,440
I mean, real bad one.

83
00:07:07,440 --> 00:07:17,680
I think a great way to ask this question would be like, could you give me a rundown as to how this system will work in typical use case of the public?

84
00:07:17,680 --> 00:07:18,580
Yeah, for sure.

85
00:07:18,580 --> 00:07:24,720
So, you know, it takes a little bit of a, the things we have to suspend our disbelief.

86
00:07:24,720 --> 00:07:28,140
First, a Flux MP has been voted in in your electorate.

87
00:07:28,140 --> 00:07:30,100
So that's important.

88
00:07:30,100 --> 00:07:35,300
But, you know, you're sitting on your couch, in your NICs, and an issue comes up.

89
00:07:35,300 --> 00:07:39,380
You're scrolling through your Facebook feed, and an issue comes up that's being debated.

90
00:07:39,380 --> 00:07:46,280
You would go to the App Store, or you can go to the website, either or, but specifically the App Store, and you download an app.

91
00:07:46,280 --> 00:07:54,420
The app allows you to login, create a user, or create a password, create an account, and you login using your federal electoral role details.

92
00:07:54,420 --> 00:07:58,420
So these are all verified by the government that you are one person.

93
00:07:58,420 --> 00:08:06,040
Then it would tell you, you know, obviously you're electorates, state level, federal level, and then the upcoming bills in parliament.

94
00:08:06,040 --> 00:08:15,440
So this is going to be voted on in four days, this is going to be voted in three days, and it would allow you to vote, yes, no, or choose not to vote on those ones.

95
00:08:15,440 --> 00:08:19,220
Then obviously say you really like an issue, click on it.

96
00:08:19,220 --> 00:08:31,800
It'll give you the synopsis of the bill, maybe give you some links to the parties, like the proposing party's information, maybe some counter information proposed by other political parties.

97
00:08:31,800 --> 00:08:40,059
This is definitely a level where we don't want to be proposing any information, so you won't find information from Flux, but you might be able to find the information that the other parties have put up.

98
00:08:40,059 --> 00:08:43,059
And then, yeah, you would vote yes or no if you wanted to.

99
00:08:43,059 --> 00:08:51,380
You'd be given the results of your entire electorate, and then a little button down the bottom to post to Twitter, post to Facebook, email my representative.

100
00:08:51,380 --> 00:08:56,840
That'd be a really basic being hit by a bill that you really cared about and acting on that bill.

101
00:08:58,120 --> 00:09:02,220
So, I am kind of curious as to one key aspects.

102
00:09:02,220 --> 00:09:16,640
Your system relies on the use of technology and smartphones, and there will be concerns from the public about the security and viability of technology-based electoral system.

103
00:09:16,640 --> 00:09:17,440
Yeah, for sure.

104
00:09:17,440 --> 00:09:18,460
It's a big tech one.

105
00:09:18,460 --> 00:09:28,760
Tech security is something that I guess is initially very scary, and especially if you're not in that industry, you know, even I am, quote unquote, in the industry, but I can't read the code.

106
00:09:28,760 --> 00:09:32,900
We could tie it to, say, like the Iowa election scandal.

107
00:09:32,900 --> 00:09:34,000
Is it scandal?

108
00:09:34,000 --> 00:09:35,680
Or kerfuffle in America?

109
00:09:35,680 --> 00:09:37,080
Kerfuffle, good term.

110
00:09:37,080 --> 00:09:43,980
Yeah, that's pretty perfect, because that exact fault was an actual fault in the code.

111
00:09:43,980 --> 00:09:46,020
Like it had been coded poorly.

112
00:09:46,020 --> 00:09:51,800
But it'll still, in people's psyche, just be an app broke and it screwed up the vote.

113
00:09:52,140 --> 00:09:56,220
You know, the tech gets reduced down so quickly.

114
00:09:56,220 --> 00:09:59,440
On a tech forefront, it is blockchain based voting.

115
00:09:59,440 --> 00:10:02,040
So you know the ledger is immutable.

116
00:10:02,040 --> 00:10:06,800
We do have the strongest security and anonymization in industry.

117
00:10:06,800 --> 00:10:08,260
You know, there is no other way.

118
00:10:08,260 --> 00:10:13,640
It's the same stuff that protects your bank, gets your banking and all your online communication.

119
00:10:15,720 --> 00:10:18,980
There is a level where it's open source.

120
00:10:18,980 --> 00:10:19,720
You can read it.

121
00:10:21,000 --> 00:10:24,840
If it's got a flaw, people will find it.

122
00:10:24,840 --> 00:10:27,980
And right now, we are telling you, there are no flaws.

123
00:10:27,980 --> 00:10:34,180
And you got to understand that, like most people are probably not technologically literate in the idea of the blockchain.

124
00:10:34,180 --> 00:10:51,340
And so I imagine part of the aspects to getting your story out there and getting traction in the public about your Flux system is you probably need to have a bit more acceptance in the idea of relying in blockchain.

125
00:10:51,340 --> 00:10:57,060
Yeah, it's funny, even in just three years, I've been with Flux.

126
00:10:57,060 --> 00:11:04,340
It's even how much we have to explain blockchain now compared to back three years ago is markedly less.

127
00:11:04,340 --> 00:11:05,720
We definitely still have to.

128
00:11:05,720 --> 00:11:09,140
There is a certain, it is still freaky new technology.

129
00:11:09,140 --> 00:11:10,460
But I think there's at least enough acceptance.

130
00:11:10,720 --> 00:11:17,840
People understand crypto, blockchain, it's something to do with saving and storing money and being anonymous.

131
00:11:17,840 --> 00:11:20,840
People at least have this rough idea of how it works now.

132
00:11:20,840 --> 00:11:27,700
Yeah, and with that acceptance, it's a lot easier to be like, so you can see how that could be used for voting, yes?

133
00:11:27,700 --> 00:11:33,940
As opposed to having to really explain how the vote worked, and how the security works, and how the works.

134
00:11:33,940 --> 00:11:35,340
It's getting there.

135
00:11:35,560 --> 00:11:42,160
It's one of those ones you really just have to put up and be like, it works, and you can't prove us wrong.

136
00:11:42,160 --> 00:11:44,840
And the people that can prove us wrong agree with us.

137
00:11:44,840 --> 00:11:47,480
So what do you want?

138
00:11:47,480 --> 00:11:54,660
Hi, and thanks for listening to this bonus content of Designing Open Democracy, talk with Ben Ballingall.

139
00:11:54,660 --> 00:12:02,700
If you are interested in this talk and you haven't heard the original talk, I recommend you to check out the last episode and give it a listen.

140
00:12:02,700 --> 00:12:06,940
Oh, and if you are in Melbourne, Australia, don't forget to check out our physical meetup.

141
00:12:06,940 --> 00:12:11,780
Each month, we cover a different topic on relating to democracy.

142
00:12:11,780 --> 00:12:17,020
Our next meetup will be likely to be about cooperatives, so I hope to see you then.

143
00:12:17,040 --> 00:12:20,020
Else, see you in the next podcast episode.

144
00:12:20,020 --> 00:12:20,320
Cheers.
